snippet.textDisplay: I saw this guy in a gym here in China. He looked...thick and compact. Thats the only way I can describe him, he was around 175 cm tall and probably weighed around 90kg, around 30 years old. You could tell that he worked out but he was in no way ripped or shredded,  not fat, just thick and compact. I see this guy bench 6:s on 200kg and 4:s on 220kg, just insane considering there are so many guys so much bigger than him that probably never will be able to reach those weights, even these beasts here struggle a little. I asked him about it and he said that he only felt it in his tricpes, never in his chest for some reason. He was also under the impression that this was "normal weights" in the west like if everyone could do it, blew my mind. I never asked what his max was but Im sure it was a lot. I guess some people are just genetically gifted and they dont even know about it.

Hey, I'm 5'9 (176cm) and 64kg (143.3lbs) at 16 years old
I just started working out and I want to know how many sets and reps of each exercise I should do if I want to build muscles.
My dad isn't a professional but he advised me to do 10 reps of 3 sets for each exercise to build muscles, but I read somewhere else that I should do 6-7 reps of 5 sets.
Just wanted to hear from someone who actually lifts and built large masses of muscles successfully
